<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>papillosus</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Adenostoma</i> <i>fasciculatum</i>, <i>Arctostaphylos</i> <i>glandulosa</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>cuneatus</i>, <i>Heteromeles</i> <i>arbutifolia</i>, <i>Quercus</i> <i>berberidifolia</i>, <i>Quercus</i> <i>wislizeni</i>, <i>Salvia</i> <i>mellifera</i> and <i>Toxicodendron</i> <i>diversilobum</i>. Emergent trees may be present at low cover, including <i>Pinus</i> <i>coulteri</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>ponderosa</i>, <i>Quercus</i> <i>agrifolia</i>, <i>Quercus</i> <i>chrysolepis</i> or <i>Umbellularia</i> <i>californica</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 5 m; canopy is intermittent to continuous. Herbaceous layer is sparse. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Ceanothus papillosus</i> > 30% relative cover in shrub canopy (Borchert et al. 2004).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Variable topography. Soils are moderately deep and well drained.  </div>
</div>

        
