<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ceanothus papillosus </i>is an evergreen shrub with rigid branches that grows to 5 m in height. At 5 years, shrubs begin producing seed, which is explosively cast from plants as their capsules break. Most of the seed drops beneath the crowns of the shrubs. Seed predation by small mammals and insects may be severe, but with time, seeds collect in the duff and soil as a seed bank. Heat stimulates germination by increasing permeability to water. <br/>
<br/>
The <i>Ceanothus papillosus </i>alliance exists from the San Francisco Bay area south to Baja California as var. <i>papillosus. </i>The low-growing form (var. <i>roweanus</i>) is restricted to the Santa Ynez Mountains in Santa Barbara Co. (Fross and Wilken 2006). It is primarily restricted to serpentine and only common after fire (Vogl 1973). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Ceanothus papillosus </i>usually associates with <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum, </i>hence the name Wartleaf ceanothus-chamise alliance given by Borchert et al. (2004) for stands that they described in the northern Santa Lucia Mountains of Monterey Co. However, the presence of <i>C. papillosus </i>is typically twice that of <i>A. fasciculatum </i>in these stands. Similar stands also occur in the Gabilan Range in northeastern Monterey Co. and adjacent San Benito Co. We include these stands here. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
