    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aj-k). Small, isolated stands occur at Cone Peak Gradient RNA (Cheng 2004) and elsewhere in the Santa Lucia Mountains (Shreve 1927, Borchert et al. 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ae-f). Small, isolated stands occur in the interior Santa Lucia Mountains (Borchert et al. 2004) and Gabilan Range.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bf). Small, isolated stands may occur in the Santa Ana Mountains with <i>Pinus attenuata</i> where both are present on serpentine (Vogl 1973).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Repeated short-interval fires deplete the seed bank. The genus is well suited for use in rehabilitation because of rapid growth rates and an ability to improve soil fertility through fixing nitrogen. </div>
</div>

    

    

    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
